<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="81" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="81">
<taxonomicName class="Sordariomycetes" family="Ceratostomataceae" genus="Microthecium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Microthecium brevirostrum" order="Melanosporales" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="brevirostrum">Microthecium brevirostrum</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="Mi." lsidName="Mi. fallax" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" rank="species" species="fallax">Mi. fallax</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="Mi." lsidName="Mi. fimbriatum" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" rank="species" species="fimbriatum">Mi. fimbriatum</taxonomicName>
produce ostiolate ascomata and ellipsoidal to citriform, often plataniform, smooth-walled ascospores with an apiculate germ pore at each end. 
<taxonomicName class="Sordariomycetes" family="Ceratostomataceae" genus="Microthecium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Microthecium fimbriatum" order="Melanosporales" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="fimbriatum">Microthecium fimbriatum</taxonomicName>
is easily distinguished by its smaller (100-110 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
diam.), reddish ascomata, while 
<taxonomicName genus="Mi." lsidName="Mi. fallax" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" rank="species" species="fallax">Mi. fallax</taxonomicName>
differs in the production of bulbils.
</paragraph>
